<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title><%= pageTitle %> – Art of the Orient</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
</head>
<body>
  <%- include('partials/header', { headerClass, pageTitle }) %>
  <main class="main">
    <h2 class="gallery-title"><%= pageTitle %></h2>
    <section class="section-text section-text-full">
      <p>Minhwa (민화), or "painting of the people," is the vibrant Korean folk painting tradition in which tigers, magpies, peonies, and the ten symbols of longevity populate a world suffused with symbolism and communal joy. Created by anonymous and itinerant painters for ordinary households, Minhwa combines bold color, simplified forms, and auspicious themes — from chaekgeori still lifes to tiger-and-magpie compositions — and remains one of Korea's most beloved and recognizable painting styles.</p>
    </section>
  </main>
  <script src="/js/nav.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
